message.content:
We first note that in the “Initial” (as of 2023‑12‑31) there is a “Fixed Assets” item of 5,000,000.00. In later transactions the only entry that “eats” into the fixed assets account is depreciation. In our list we see two depreciation entries:

• Depreciation20240101001: 45,752.22  
• Depreciation20240201002: 45,750.84

Add these together:
 45,752.22 + 45,750.84 = 91,503.06

No “addition” to fixed assets (in the sense of capital purchases) is seen among the other “Purchase” lines because they are operating purchases rather than fixed asset acquisitions.

Thus the fixed assets net end value is computed as

 Fixed Assets, End = Initial Fixed Assets – (Total Depreciation)
   = 5,000,000.00 – 91,503.06
   = 4,908,496.94

Presenting our result in the required JSON format:

{"solution": {'fixed assets net Initial Value': '5000000.00', 'fixed assets net End Value': '4908496.94'}}
